{"slug": "shaman", "root": "shaman", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a spirit-mediating healer", "definition": "A shaman is a spirit-mediating specialist — one who enters trance to travel among spirits, heal, and divine on a community's behalf. In fantasy the shaman is the primal magic-user, close to nature and the ancestors.", "history": "Unlike almost every other word here, *shaman* is not European: English took it in the 1690s from Russian *shamán*, from the Tungusic (Evenki) *šamán* of Siberia. Anthropology then stretched it to cover trance-specialists worldwide — a generalization scholars now handle with care. Magic makes *Shaman* a major creature type, skewing green and red, the colors of nature and primal fury.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. shaman", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "commentary": "'Shaman' is a genuine Tungusic word (Evenki *šamán*), but *shamanism* — the universal category — is largely a Western construction. From Mircea Eliade onward, anthropology stretched a specific Siberian office to cover every trance-specialist on earth, and critics such as Alice Kehoe and Andrei Znamenski have shown how much that flattening owes to Romantic primitivism and a Cold-War appetite for a single 'archaic technique of ecstasy.' The word names something historically precise; the *-ism* names a scholarly habit worth distrusting.", "commentary_sources": [{"label": "Alice B. Kehoe, Shamans and Religion", "where": "Reference"}, {"label": "Andrei Znamenski, The Beauty of the Primitive", "where": "Reference"}, {"label": "Ronald Hutton, Shamans: Siberian Spirituality and the Western Imagination", "where": "Reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Russian shamán ← Evenki (Tungusic) šamán", "first": "English 1690s", "note": "A late loan into English from Siberian religion; sometimes further linked to Sanskrit śramaṇa (‘ascetic’), though that’s contested.", "hook": "The one clearly non-European word in the magic lexicon.", "lang": 